{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17624139","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17624139"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:16:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:16:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16892"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16892","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16892"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.73,0.25,0,0.01,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9582"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76332"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9582","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9582"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16892"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61841"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1003"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5007"},{"type":"tags","id":"5020"},{"type":"tags","id":"5090"},{"type":"tags","id":"9833"},{"type":"tags","id":"10089"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22611"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22614"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76332","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76332"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EVitamin K plays a crucial role in blood coagulation and is obtained through diet and intestinal bacterial synthesis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary physiological function of vitamin K?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Enables gamma-carboxylation of clotting factors","Binds to clotting factors to activate them","Facilitates calcium absorption in the intestine","Activates protein C and S directly","Component of direct clotting pathway"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary physiological function of vitamin K is to enable \u003Cstrong\u003Egamma-carboxylation of clotting factors\u003C/strong\u003E II, VII, IX, and X in the liver. This post-translational modification is essential for these proteins to bind calcium and become functionally active in the coagulation cascade.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBinds to clotting factors to activate them\u003C/strong\u003E - vitamin K enables carboxylation but does not directly bind to or activate clotting factors\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFacilitates calcium absorption in the intestine\u003C/strong\u003E - this is a function of vitamin D, not vitamin K\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActivates protein C and S directly\u003C/strong\u003E - while protein C and S require vitamin K for carboxylation, vitamin K does not directly activate these proteins\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComponent of direct clotting pathway\u003C/strong\u003E - vitamin K is a cofactor for protein modification but is not itself a component of the clotting cascade\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EVitamin K deficiency can occur in malabsorption syndromes, prolonged antibiotic therapy (reducing bacterial synthesis), or functionally in the instance of warfarin therapy, which antagonises vitamin K function.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Vitamin K is essential for the carboxylation of clotting factors II, VII, IX, and X in the liver, leading 